,"1167–1242":"1167–1242","1171–1200":"1171–1200","1164–1203":"1164–1203","1185–1260":"1185–1260","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1135–1189":"1135–1189","12 July 1198":"12 juli 1198","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1172":"1172","1260":"1260","1171":"1171","Abt 1164":"circa 1164","1129":"1129","um 1182":"circa 1182","1203":"1203","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","1166":"1166","27 April 1172":"27 april 1172","1172-1198":"van 1172 to 1198","about 1185":"circa 1185","Herzogtum Kleve, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Kleve"},"en":{"Abt 1164–12 July 1198":"about 1164–12 July 1198","1164–1198":"1164–1198","1166–Female":"1166–Deceased","1167–1242":"1167–1242","1171–1200":"1171–1200","1164–1203":"1164–1203","1185–1260":"1185–1260","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1135–1189":"1135–1189","12 July 1198":"12 July 1198","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1172":"1172","1260":"1260","1171":"1171","Abt 1164":"about 1164","1129":"1129","um 1182":"about 1182","1203":"1203","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","1166":"1166","27 April 1172":"27 April 1172","1172-1198":"from 1172 to 1198","about 1185":"about 1185","Herzogtum Kleve, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Cleves","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Kleve","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from Kleve (earlier Cleve) in Lower Rhineland, Westphalia, or Schleswig-Holstein. The placename probably derives from an old topographic term <i>cleve</i> ‘swamp’. Compare   Cleve  .","German: variant of   Klever   2.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Kleiva, from Old Norse <i>kleif</i>, <i>klif</i> ‘cliff, rocky ascent with a road or path’."],"variants":[{"name":"Klever","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Ulrike.","German and Dutch: habitational name for someone from Kleve in the Rhineland or Schleswig-Holstein (see   Kleve   1).","German: from Middle Low German <i>klēver</i> ‘clover, meadow’, also ‘resin, turpentine’, hence a metonymic occupational name either for a farmer who grew clover or for someone who collected resin and distilled turpentine. In the Alemannic area this was also a nickname for a bungler. Compare   Cleaver   and   Clever  ."]},{"name":"Kleven","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Berger, Hjalmer, Jalmer, Knute, Maren, Obert, Thor, Thorval.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads all over Norway named Kleven, from the definite singular form of   Kleve  . Compare   Cleven   and   Cleveland  .","Dutch and German: rare variant of   Cleven  ."]},{"name":"Cleve","meanings":["English: variant of   Cliff  .","German: variant of   Kleve  ."]}]},{"name":"Dietrich","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>þeud</i> ‘people’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.  See  <b>Terry</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Diederick","meanings":["from <i>þeud</i> ‘people’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.  See  <b>Terry</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dietrich V. von Kleve was born about 1164, in Cleves, his father, Dietrich IV. von Kleve, was 36 and his mother, Adelheid von Sulzbach, was 31. He married Margaretha van Holland about 1182. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 12 July 1198, in his hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"Abt 1164–12 July 1198":"umbes 1164–12. ju